  <subsection>
    <title>Introduction:</title>
    <p>
      In this activity,
      students will find tangent lines to various functions,
      and then will display the tangent lines and function on the same graph.
    </p>
    <p>
      To find the tangent line to a function <m>f(x)</m> at <m>x = a</m>,
      two pieces of information are needed:
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            The point, <m>(a, f(a))</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            The slope of the tangent line, <m>f'(a)</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    <aside>
      <p>
        A detailed example of finding and plotting tangent lines is described on <xref ref="subsec_equation_of_tangent_line">page</xref>.
      </p>
    </aside>
    <p>
      Plugging these two pieces of information into the point-slope form of a line gives the following equation.
      <md>
        <mrow>y - y_0 \amp = m_{tan} \cdot (x-x_0) \nonumber</mrow>
        <mrow>y - f(a) \amp = f'(a) \cdot (x-a) \nonumber</mrow>
        <mrow xml:id="eq_tanline" number="yes">y \amp = f'(a) \cdot (x-a) + f(a)</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
    <p>
          <idx><h>lines</h><h>tangent line</h></idx>
          <idx><h>lines</h><h>slope of a tangent line</h></idx>
      We will use equation <xref ref="eq_tanline"/> for the following exercises.
    </p>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Exercises:</title>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Consider the function <m>f(x) = \sqrt{9 - x}</m>.
          <ol>
            <aside>
              <p>
                Be sure to choose different names for each tangent line.
                If you assign a new expression to an old name,
                the new expression will overwrite what was previously assigned.
              </p>
            </aside>
            <li>
              <p>
                Define the equations of the tangent lines at <m>x=0</m> and <m>x=5</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Plot <m>f(x)</m> and the two tangent lines on the same axes.
            <idx><h>plot</h><h>multiple functions</h></idx>
        <aside>
                  <p>
                    Since you are plotting more than one tangent line on the same axes,
                    it is a good idea to specify plot colours.
                  </p>
                </aside>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Consider the function <m>g(x)=x{ e}^{x}</m>.
            <idx><h>mathematical functions</h><h>exponential</h></idx>
        <aside>
            <p>
              In Maple, <c>exp(x)</c> is used to denote the exponential function,
              <m>{ e}^x</m>.
            </p>
          </aside>
            <idx><h>mathematical functions</h><h>exponential</h></idx>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Define the equations of the tangent lines at <m>x=1</m> and <m>x=-1</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Plot <m>g(x)</m> and the two tangent lines on the same axes.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Consider the function <m>h(x)=x^3-x^2-9x+9</m>.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Find the <m>x</m>-values where the function has tangent lines with slope equal to <m>1</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Find the <m>x</m>-values where the function has horizontal tangent lines.
            <idx><h>lines</h><h>horizontal tangent line</h></idx>
        <aside>
                  <p>
                    To solve part (b),
                    you need to remember what the slope of a horizontal tangent line is.
                  </p>
                </aside>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </subsection>
